msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:114
msgid ""
"The integer signedness case deserves emphasis. In Rust, `i32` and `u32` are "
"different types. In LLVM, both are just `i32`. The sign information shifts "
"to the operations: a signed less-than comparison is `icmp slt`, an unsigned "
"one is `icmp ult`. The type converter drops the signedness, and the "
"operation converters pick it back up when they emit comparison and division "
"instructions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:122
msgid "Argument Scalarization"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:124
msgid ""
"Kernel entry points need special treatment. The CUDA driver doesn't "
"understand Rust fat pointers, so `&[f32]` has to arrive as a separate "
"pointer and length on both sides of the ABI. Structs and closures by value, "
"on the other hand, do match a single host packet slot, so the kernel entry "
"takes them as one byval `.param` -- otherwise the device would expect N "
"flattened arguments and the host would only push one, mismatching every "
"later slice."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:132
msgid ""
"The lowering pass therefore distinguishes the kernel-entry rule from the "
"internal-call rule:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:0
msgid "MIR kernel param"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:0
msgid "LLVM kernel signature"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:0
msgid "`&[f32]`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:0
msgid "`ptr addrspace(1) %ptr, i64 %len`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:0
msgid "`T` (scalar)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:0
msgid "passthrough"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:0
msgid "`struct { a, b }`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:0
msgid "one byval `{a, b}` value"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:0
msgid "closure (N captures)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:0
msgid "one byval closure-struct value"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:0
msgid "zero-sized aggregate"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:0
msgid "dropped (no LLVM arg, no host packet slot)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:143
msgid ""
"The slice case still uses the classic reconstruct-from-flattened pattern in "
"the entry block:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:146
msgid ""
"MIR:  fn kernel(slice: &[f32])\n"
"      → entry arg: %slice : MirSliceType\n"
"\n"
"LLVM: fn kernel(ptr addrspace(1) %ptr, i64 %len)\n"
"      → entry block reconstructs:\n"
"          %slice  = insertvalue {ptr, i64} undef, %ptr, 0\n"
"          %slice2 = insertvalue {ptr, i64} %slice, %len, 1\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:156
msgid ""
"The struct/closure case skips the reconstruct -- the byval value is already "
"the right shape -- and the rest of the function sees it as if nothing "
"special happened. Internal device-to-device calls keep flattening aggregates "
"the same way they always have, so the cost of this rule lives only at the "
"kernel boundary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:164
msgid "Interesting Conversions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:166
msgid ""
"Most conversions are straightforward: `mir.add` on integers becomes `llvm."
"add`, `mir.load` becomes `llvm.load`, `mir.goto` becomes `llvm.br`. The "
"interesting cases are the ones where a single MIR operation expands into "
"multiple LLVM operations, or where GPU-specific concerns change the "
"translation entirely."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:171
msgid "Checked Arithmetic"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:173
msgid ""
"In debug builds, Rust checks every integer arithmetic operation for "
"overflow. MIR models this with operations like `mir.checked_add` that return "
"a `(result, overflow_flag)` tuple. LLVM has no such concept, but it does "
"have overflow intrinsics:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:178
msgid ""
"MIR:  %result = mir.checked_add %a, %b : i32  → mir.tuple<i32, bool>\n"
"\n"
"LLVM: %sum = add i32 %a, %b\n"
"      %overflow = extractvalue {i32, i1} @llvm.sadd.with.overflow.i32(%a, "
"%b), 1\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:185
msgid ""
"The overflow flag feeds into an assert that the MIR importer already lowered "
"to a conditional branch targeting an unreachable block. On the GPU, this "
"effectively means: if you manage to trigger integer overflow, the kernel "
"traps. Not the most graceful error handling, but the CUDA toolchain does not "
"support stack unwinding today."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:191
msgid "Shared Memory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:193
msgid ""
"Shared memory in CUDA is block-scoped SRAM -- fast, small, and declared "
"statically. In `dialect-mir`, it is a `mir.shared_alloc` operation. In LLVM "
"IR, shared memory must be a module-level global variable in address space 3:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:197
msgid ""
"MIR:  %shmem = mir.shared_alloc : mir.array<f32, 256>\n"
"\n"
"LLVM: @shmem_0 = addrspace(3) global [256 x float] zeroinitializer\n"
"      %ptr = addrspacecast [256 x float] addrspace(3)* @shmem_0 to ptr\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:204
msgid ""
"The `addrspacecast` produces a generic pointer that the rest of the function "
"can use without worrying about address spaces. The NVPTX backend in LLVM "
"handles the rest -- it knows that `addrspace(3)` means shared memory and "
"generates the appropriate `st.shared` / `ld.shared` instructions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:209
msgid "Enum Lowering"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:211
msgid ""
"Rust enums are algebraically rich. LLVM has no concept of tagged unions. The "
"lowering pass bridges the gap by representing enums as a struct with two "
"fields: a discriminant (telling you which variant is active) and a payload "
"area sized to the largest variant:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:216
msgid ""
"MIR:  %opt = mir.construct_enum \"Some\", (%val) : mir.enum<\"Option_i32\">\n"
"\n"
"LLVM: %tmp = insertvalue { i8, [4 x i8] } zeroinitializer, i8 1, 0\n"
"      %result = insertvalue { i8, [4 x i8] } %tmp, <val into payload area>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:223
msgid ""
"The discriminant is `i8 1` because `Some` is variant 1 of `Option`. The "
"payload is `[4 x i8]` -- four bytes, enough to hold an `i32`. Variant access "
"works in reverse: read the discriminant, branch on it, then `extractvalue` "
"the payload and bitcast to the expected type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:228
msgid ""
"It is not elegant, but it is exactly how C compilers have handled tagged "
"unions for decades. LLVM's optimizer is quite good at cleaning up the "
"redundant insertvalue/extractvalue chains."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:234
msgid "GPU Intrinsic Conversion"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:236
msgid ""
"`dialect-nvvm` operations -- thread indexing, warp shuffles, barriers, TMA "
"bulk copies -- are not lowered to generic LLVM dialect operations. They are "
"lowered to either LLVM intrinsic calls or inline PTX assembly, depending on "
"whether LLVM has a built-in intrinsic for the operation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:241
msgid "Strategy 1: LLVM Intrinsic Call"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:243
msgid ""
"For operations where LLVM already provides a target-specific intrinsic, the "
"conversion emits a `call` to that intrinsic:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:246
msgid ""
"nvvm.read_ptx_sreg_tid_x\n"
"  → call i32 @llvm_nvvm_read_ptx_sreg_tid_x()\n"
"\n"
"nvvm.shfl_sync_bfly_i32\n"
"  → call i32 @llvm_nvvm_shfl_sync_bfly_i32(i32 -1, i32 %val, i32 %mask, i32 "
"31)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:254
msgid ""
"Notice the warp shuffle: the user-facing `cuda_device` API takes two "
"arguments (value and lane mask), but the LLVM intrinsic takes four "
"(membermask, value, delta, clamp). The lowering pass fills in the missing "
"arguments -- `membermask = -1` (all lanes) and `clamp = 31` (full warp "
"width) -- so the user never has to think about them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:260
msgid "Strategy 2: Inline PTX Assembly"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:262
msgid ""
"Newer GPU instructions often lack LLVM intrinsics. For these, the lowering "
"pass emits inline PTX assembly using LLVM's `asm` syntax:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:265
msgid ""
"nvvm.wgmma_fence_sync\n"
"  → call void asm sideeffect convergent \"wgmma.fence.sync.aligned;\", "
"\"\"()\n"
"\n"
"nvvm.mbarrier_arrive\n"
"  → call i64 asm sideeffect convergent \"mbarrier.arrive.shared.b64 $0, [$1];"
"\", \"=l,r\"(ptr %bar)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:273
msgid ""
"The `convergent` attribute is critical here. It tells LLVM: \"Do not move, "
"duplicate, or speculate this instruction across control flow.\" Without it, "
"LLVM might hoist a barrier out of a conditional branch or sink a warp-level "
"instruction past a sync point, resulting in a GPU that hangs or computes "
"garbage -- neither of which produces a helpful error message."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:281
msgid "Block Arguments to PHI Nodes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:283
msgid ""
"Pliron IR (MLIR-like) uses **block arguments** for value flow between basic "
"blocks. LLVM uses **PHI nodes**. They express the same concept -- \"this "
"value comes from different predecessors\" -- but the syntax is different "
"enough that the export step needs a real transformation, not just pretty-"
"printing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:288
msgid "Pliron style (block arguments):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:290
msgid ""
"^loop_header(%sum: f32, %i: i64):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    br ^loop_header(%new_sum, %new_i)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:296
msgid "LLVM IR style (PHI nodes):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:298
msgid ""
"loop_header:\n"
"    %sum = phi float [ 0.0, %preheader ], [ %new_sum, %body ]\n"
"    %i = phi i64 [ 0, %preheader ], [ %new_i, %body ]\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:304
msgid "The exporter handles this conversion with a two-pass approach:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:306
msgid ""
"**Pre-pass: name every value.** Before emitting any code, the exporter walks "
"all blocks and assigns sequential SSA names (`%v0`, `%v1`, ...) to every "
"value. This is critical because PHI nodes can reference values from blocks "
"that appear *later* in the listing -- loop back-edges point forward in the "
"text but backward in the control flow. Without pre-naming, those references "
"would be undefined."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:313
msgid ""
"**Build a predecessor map.** For each block, the exporter collects "
"`(predecessor_block, values_passed)` pairs by inspecting every branch "
"instruction in the function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:317
msgid ""
"**Emit PHI nodes.** At the entry of each non-entry block, the exporter emits "
"one PHI node per block argument, populated with the values and predecessor "
"labels from the predecessor map."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:321
msgid ""
"The pre-pass is the subtle part. Consider a loop: the PHI in the loop header "
"references `%new_sum` from the loop body, but the loop body appears *after* "
"the header in the textual output. If we assigned names on-the-fly during "
"emission, `%new_sum` would not have a name yet. The pre-pass eliminates this "
"problem by naming everything upfront."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:329
msgid "Debug Locations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:331
msgid ""
"rustc already knows where most MIR operations came from in the source "
"program. cuda-oxide preserves that information as it lowers the kernel:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:334
msgid ""
"rustc Span\n"
"  ↓\n"
"pliron Location\n"
"  ↓\n"
"LLVM !dbg metadata\n"
"  ↓\n"
"PTX .loc / DWARF\n"
"  ↓\n"
"cuda-gdb source line\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:346
msgid "The common case is a source line in the same file as the function:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:348
msgid ""
"define ptx_kernel void @vecadd(...) !dbg !func {\n"
"  %idx = call i64 @cuda_device____internal__index_1d(...), !dbg !loc\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"!loc = !DILocation(line: 39, column: 13, scope: !func)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:356
msgid ""
"That says: \"this instruction belongs to line 39, column 13, inside this "
"function.\" It is just enough for cuda-gdb to stop on the right Rust line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:359
msgid "Cross-file spans"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:361
msgid ""
"Some source spans point into helper files. For example, a kernel in `src/"
"main.rs` may step into `cuda-device/src/thread.rs` when calling `thread::"
"index_1d()`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:365
msgid ""
"The exporter must not attach `thread.rs:292` directly to the kernel's `src/"
"main.rs` scope. That would tell the debugger \"line 292 of main.rs\", which "
"is the kind of small lie that turns debugging into archaeology."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:369
msgid "Instead, cuda-oxide creates a file-specific debug scope:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:371
msgid ""
"src/main.rs function scope\n"
"  |\n"
"  +-- cuda-device/src/thread.rs file scope\n"
"        |\n"
"        +-- line 292, column 19\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:379
msgid "In LLVM metadata this looks like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:381
msgid ""
"!thread_scope = !DILexicalBlockFile(scope: !kernel_scope, file: !"
"thread_file, discriminator: 0)\n"
"!loc = !DILocation(line: 292, column: 19, scope: !thread_scope)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:386
msgid ""
"When Pliron gives an explicit callsite location, the exporter also records "
"where the helper code was reached from:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:389
msgid ""
"!call = !DILocation(line: 39, column: 13, scope: !kernel_scope)\n"
"!loc = !DILocation(line: 292, column: 19, scope: !thread_scope, inlinedAt: !"
"call)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:394
msgid ""
"Read that as: \"we are executing `thread.rs:292`, reached from `main.rs:39`."
"\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:396
msgid "Variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:398
msgid ""
"Full debug mode adds the first variable records on top of line locations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:400
msgid ""
"%tid_slot = alloca i32\n"
"call void @llvm.dbg.declare(metadata ptr %tid_slot, metadata !tid, metadata !"
"DIExpression())\n"
"\n"
"!tid = !DILocalVariable(name: \"tid\", scope: !func, file: !file, line: 31, "
"type: !u32)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:407
msgid "The model is the one every debug build uses:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:409
msgid "dbg.declare -> \"this source variable lives at this address\"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:413
msgid ""
"Because the address is stable for the variable's whole scope, cuda-gdb can "
"read it at any breakpoint inside that scope. To keep those addresses real, "
"full-debug is a `-G`-style build: it **skips** Pliron `mem2reg` (so the "
"stack slots survive), **skips** LLVM `opt -O2`, and runs `llc` at `-O0`. "
"Promoting a local to an SSA value would shrink its inspectable range to its "
"register's liveness, which is exactly how an optimized build ends up showing "
"in-scope locals as `<optimized out>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:421
msgid ""
"The aggregate locals (structs, tuples, arrays) get a `DICompositeType` whose "
"members carry rustc's real layout offsets, so `info locals` prints their "
"fields:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:424
msgid "out = DisjointSlice {ptr: 0x..., len: 1}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:428
msgid ""
"Pliron `mem2reg` still has a promotion-aware salvage path: when it promotes "
"a debug-tagged slot it emits a `mir.dbg_value` (\"this source variable has "
"this SSA value here\") that lowers to `llvm.dbg.value`. That is the "
"groundwork for a future *optimized* debug tier; the current `full` tier does "
"not run `mem2reg`, so it relies on `dbg.declare` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:434
msgid "Variable scopes and inlining"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:436
msgid ""
"Variable metadata has one extra rule: `arg: 1` means \"formal argument #1 of "
"the function named by this debug scope.\" After MIR inlining, two variables "
"in one kernel body can both honestly be `arg: 1`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:440
msgid ""
"caller kernel:  data  -> arg #1 of caller\n"
"inlined helper: self  -> arg #1 of helper\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:445
msgid ""
"So cuda-oxide carries rustc's MIR source-scope table alongside each "
"translated function. A local debug record stores only the source-scope id it "
"came from; the LLVM exporter turns that id into the right DWARF shape:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:449
msgid ""
"kernel DISubprogram\n"
"  |\n"
"  +-- helper DISubprogram\n"
"        |\n"
"        +-- DILocation(..., inlinedAt: kernel callsite)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:457
msgid ""
"This is why `data` and `self` can both keep `arg: 1` without LLVM rejecting "
"the module as contradictory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:460
msgid ""
"The current placement is conservative. If `mem2reg` creates a block argument "
"that acts like a PHI value, cuda-oxide records the variable at the promoted "
"load/store source point. It does not yet add an eager block-entry debug "
"record just because the compiler created a join value:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:465
msgid ""
"then -> merge(10)\n"
"else -> merge(20)\n"
"\n"
"merge(%x):\n"
"  ... old load site becomes dbg.value(%x, \"x\") ...\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:473
msgid ""
"That is correct but not maximally precise. A future pass can make `x` "
"visible earlier in the merge block once the source location and lexical "
"scope rules are clear."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:477
msgid ""
"One more compiler-maintainer detail: `mir.dbg_value` is debug-only, but "
"inside Pliron today it still has a normal operand use. cuda-oxide therefore "
"does not run Pliron DCE after this debug salvage point. If we add that "
"later, DCE needs to treat debug uses as non-semantic, the same way LLVM "
"treats `dbg.value`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:482
msgid ""
"PHI nodes generated by the exporter normally do not get `!dbg`: they are SSA "
"bookkeeping, not source operations the user wrote. Later variable metadata "
"can refer to PHI values through `dbg.value`, but the PHI itself should not "
"become a surprise stop in cuda-gdb."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:489
msgid "Symbol Name Sanitization"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:491
msgid ""
"Function names flow through several stages, each applying its own "
"constraints:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:493
msgid ""
"rustc_public (FQDN)            helper_fn::cuda_oxide_device_<hash>_vecadd\n"
"  ↓ body.rs (:: → __)\n"
"dialect-mir                    helper_fn__cuda_oxide_device_<hash>_vecadd\n"
"  ↓ call.rs (:: → __)\n"
"LLVM dialect                   helper_fn__cuda_oxide_device_<hash>_vecadd\n"
"  ↓ llvm-export (strip prefix)\n"
"Textual LLVM IR                @vecadd\n"
"  ↓ llc\n"
"PTX                            vecadd\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:505
msgid "Three conversions happen along this path:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:507
msgid ""
"**`::` to `__`** -- Both `body.rs` (function definitions) and `call.rs` "
"(call targets) replace Rust path separators with double underscores to "
"produce valid pliron/LLVM identifiers. Since both sides apply the same "
"conversion, definitions and call sites match."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:512
msgid ""
"**Device prefix stripping** -- `export.rs` strips the reserved "
"`cuda_oxide_device_<hash>_` prefix (and any preceding FQDN crate prefix) "
"from `#[device]` function names via `reserved_oxide_symbols::"
"device_base_name`. This prefix exists for MIR-level detection but should not "
"appear in the final LLVM IR, PTX, or LTOIR output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:518
msgid ""
"**Device extern prefix stripping** -- For `#[device] unsafe extern \"C\"` "
"functions, `call.rs` strips the `cuda_oxide_device_extern_<hash>_` prefix "
"via `reserved_oxide_symbols::device_extern_base_name` so the LLVM IR "
"references the original symbol name exported by the external LTOIR (e.g., "
"CCCL libraries)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:525
msgid ""
"This manual sanitization will be replaced by pliron's `Legaliser` when the "
"framework is upgraded. The `Legaliser` handles `::` to `_` conversion and "
"collision detection systematically."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:532
msgid "PTX Generation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:534
msgid ""
"After the LLVM dialect is exported to a textual `.ll` file, the final step "
"is invoking `llc` -- LLVM's static compiler -- to produce PTX assembly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:537
msgid "llc -march=nvptx64 -mcpu=sm_90 kernel.ll -o kernel.ptx\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:541
msgid "Target Selection"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:543
msgid ""
"The pipeline probes for `llc` in the order below. LLVM 21 is the minimum — "
"earlier releases reject the TMA / tcgen05 / WGMMA intrinsic signatures that "
"cuda-oxide emits."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:524
msgid "Priority"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:524
msgid "Source"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:524
msgid "1st"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:524
msgid "`$CUDA_OXIDE_LLC` (if set)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:524
msgid "Caller-supplied override; whatever binary you point it at."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:524
msgid "2nd"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:524
msgid "Rust toolchain's `llvm-tools` llc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:524
msgid "`<sysroot>/lib/rustlib/<host>/bin/llc` (auto-installed via `rustup`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:524
msgid "3rd"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:524
msgid "`llc-22` on `PATH`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:524
msgid "Distro / `apt.llvm.org` install of LLVM 22."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:524
msgid "4th"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:524
msgid "`llc-21` on `PATH`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:524
msgid "Distro / `apt.llvm.org` install of LLVM 21."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:524
msgid "5th"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:524
msgid "`llc` on `PATH`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:524
msgid "Reporting fallback only; rejected at runtime if older than LLVM 21."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:555
msgid ""
"The pinned Rust toolchain (`nightly-2026-04-03`) ships LLVM 22 with NVPTX "
"enabled, so `rustup component add llvm-tools` is the recommended onboarding "
"path. The PATH probes for `llc-22` / `llc-21` are kept as a fallback for "
"users with an existing LLVM install. If none of the probes succeed the "
"pipeline fails with a clear error. You can opt into a specific (possibly "
"older) binary by setting `CUDA_OXIDE_LLC=/path/to/llc`, but simple kernels "
"are the only thing guaranteed to compile on LLVM 20 and below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:563
msgid ""
"If the selected target does not match the physical GPU, the CUDA driver JIT-"
"compiles the PTX at load time. First launch costs roughly 30ms while the "
"driver translates; subsequent launches use a cached binary. In practice, you "
"rarely notice -- the JIT is fast and the cache is persistent across runs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:568
msgid ""
"The `CUDA_OXIDE_TARGET` environment variable overrides auto-detection for "
"cases where you need a specific target. For example, `sm_100a` enables "
"Blackwell-specific `tcgen05` features that are not available under the "
"generic `sm_100` target."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:573
msgid ""
"`cargo oxide run` adds a second layer of auto-detection on top of the "
"backend's feature-based default: when neither `--arch` nor "
"`CUDA_OXIDE_TARGET` is set, it queries the compute capability of CUDA device "
"0 and forwards that to the backend so the generated module is guaranteed to "
"load on the local GPU. The full precedence is `--arch` > `CUDA_OXIDE_TARGET` "
"> host CC (for `run` only) > backend feature-based default. `cargo oxide "
"build` and `cargo oxide pipeline` deliberately skip the host-CC step so they "
"remain usable for cross-compilation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:582
msgid ""
"If the lowered module calls CUDA libdevice, cuda-oxide switches from `llc` "
"to the NVVM path automatically. It resolves the target with the same "
"precedence before choosing typed- or opaque-pointer NVVM IR. Explicit NVVM/"
"LTOIR commands still require `--arch`; the feature-based fallback applies "
"only when an ordinary build discovers that libdevice is needed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:589
msgid ""
"Why LLVM 21? The 2-D bulk TMA load intrinsic used by `tma_copy`, `gemm_sol`, "
"and `tcgen05_matmul` gained a 10-operand form with `addrspace(7)` and a "
"`cta_group` parameter in LLVM 21. Older `llc` versions reject it with "
"`Intrinsic has incorrect argument type!`. Rather than maintain separate "
"intrinsic emitters per LLVM version, we set 21 as the minimum."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:596
msgid "Atomic operations in legacy NVVM IR"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:598
msgid ""
"An “LLVM-level atomic” is an atomic instruction in the NVVM input. It is not "
"a statement about whether the GPU has atomic hardware. CUDA 12's LLVM 7 NVVM "
"dialect accepts only a subset:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:588
msgid "LLVM construct"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:588
msgid "CUDA 12 NVVM IR"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:588
msgid "cuda-oxide legacy path today"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:588
msgid "Atomic load or store"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:588
msgid "Not supported as an LLVM atomic instruction"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:588
msgid "Rejected; it needs another lowering"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:588
msgid "`fence`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:588
msgid ""
"LLVM `fence` is unsupported; an NVVM memory-barrier operation is required"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:588
msgid "Rejected pending an exact ordering/scope mapping"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:588
msgid "`cmpxchg`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:588
msgid ""
"`i32`/`i64`, plus `i128` on `compute_90+`; global/shared pointers or generic "
"pointers known to refer there"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:588
msgid ""
"Rejected pending type, address-space, alignment, and ordering validation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:588
msgid "`atomicrmw`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:588
msgid ""
"Integer `xchg`, `add`, `sub`, `and`, `or`, `xor`, `max`, `min`, `umax`, and "
"`umin` on `i32`/`i64`; `i128 xchg` on `compute_90+`; the same address-space "
"restriction"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:588
msgid "Rejected pending the same validation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:588
msgid "NVVM atomic intrinsics"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:588
msgid ""
"Provide selected additional operations, including floating-point atomic add"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:588
msgid "Not yet part of generic LLVM-atomic legalization"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:610
msgid ""
"The normal LLVM-to-PTX path keeps its existing atomic support. The "
"limitation above applies only to the legacy NVVM legalizer. cuda-oxide "
"rejects these operations until it can prove that their type, address space, "
"ordering, and scope are preserved. The legacy specification also accepts but "
"ignores `cmpxchg`'s `weak` marker and failure ordering."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:616
msgid ""
"For the exact accepted types and operations, see the [CUDA 12.4 NVVM IR "
"specification](https://docs.nvidia.com/cuda/archive/12.4.0/nvvm-ir-spec/"
"index.html)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:621
msgid "Putting It All Together"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:623
msgid ""
"Here is the full sequence of events when `lower_mir_to_llvm` processes a "
"module:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:625
msgid ""
"1. LLVM dialect types and operations are registered automatically (link-"
"time)\n"
"2. For each MirFuncOp in the module:\n"
"   a. Create `llvm.func` with flattened type signature\n"
"   b. inline_region: move `dialect-mir` blocks into the LLVM function\n"
"   c. Build entry prologue (reconstruct aggregates from flat args)\n"
"   d. Run DialectConversion:\n"
"      ├── Walk every `dialect-mir`/`dialect-nvvm` op (def-before-use order)\n"
"      ├── Invoke MirToLlvmConversion::rewrite for each op\n"
"      ├── Converter emits LLVM dialect op(s) via DialectConversionRewriter\n"
"      └── Framework patches block arg types automatically\n"
"3. Export the LLVM dialect to textual LLVM IR (.ll) (with PHI node "
"conversion)\n"
"4. Invoke llc to produce .ptx\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:640
msgid ""
"After step 4, you have a `.ptx` file that the CUDA driver can load and "
"execute. The journey from `mir.checked_add` to `add.s32` is complete."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/lowering-pipeline.md:645
msgid ""
"The lowering pipeline turns Rust-flavored IR into GPU-ready LLVM IR. For a "
"hands-on walkthrough of adding new GPU operations, see [Adding New "
"Intrinsics](adding-new-intrinsics.md)."
msgstr ""
